1 olive oil
1 portion cauliflower
1 bag baby spinach leaves
½ tin sweetcorn
20 g butter
1 tsp plain flour
¾ cup milk
1 sachet Chicken-Style Stock Powder
1 packet beef mince
1 egg
½ packet fine breadcrumbs
1 sachet barbecue seasoning
1 bag slaw mix
1 drizzle white wine vinegar
3 clove garlic
1 packet Grated Parmesan Cheese
1 packet BBQ sauce

Preheat the oven to 220°C/200°C fan-forced. Cut the cauliflower into small florets. Place the cauliflower in a baking dish. Drizzle with olive oil, season with salt and toss to coat. Roast until tender and brown around the edges, 10-15 minutes. Finely chop the garlic. Roughly chop the baby spinach leaves. Drain the sweetcorn (see ingredients).

While the cauliflower is roasting, heat a large frying pan over a medium heat. Cook the butter and 1/2 the garlic until fragrant, 1 minute. Add the plain flour and cook, stirring, until a thick paste forms, 2 minutes. Remove the pan from the heat, then slowly whisk in the milk until smooth. Stir through the chicken-style stock powder. When the cauliflower is done, add the sweetcorn to the baking dish, then pour over the creamy sauce. Evenly sprinkle over the grated Parmesan cheese and bake until golden and bubbling, 8-10 minutes.

While the cheesy cauliflower is baking, combine the beef mince, egg, fine breadcrumbs (see ingredients), the barbecue seasoning and remaining garlic in a medium bowl. Using damp hands, roll heaped spoonfuls of the beef mixture into small meatballs. Transfer to a plate. You should get 4-5 meatballs per person.

Wipe out the frying pan and return to a medium-high heat with a drizzle of olive oil. Cook the meatballs, turning, until browned and cooked through, 8-10 minutes (cook in batches if your pan is getting crowded). Remove the pan from heat, then add the BBQ sauce and toss to combine.

While the meatballs are cooking, combine the slaw mix, baby spinach leaves and a drizzle of white wine vinegar and a drizzle of olive oil in a second medium bowl. Season to taste.

Divide the BBQ beef meatballs, cheesy corn cauliflower and spinach slaw between plates. Spoon any remaining sauce from the pan over the meatballs to serve.